description.narrative: Central and decentralized health and environment authorities in targeted areas have improved capacity to legislate, budget, design, deliver and coordinate Water, Sanitation, and Hygiene (WASH) services and interventions to mitigate the impact of air pollution on child survival., which contributes to Climate Change, Disaster Risks And Envionmental Degradation, Hygiene, Safe And Equitable Water, Sanitation And Hygiene Services And Practices, Safe And Equitable Water, Sanitation And Hygiene Services And Practices (Covid), Sanitation, Wash And Emergencies, Wash â€“ General, Water Supply, Water, Sanitation And Hygiene Systems And Empowerment Of Communities, Water, Sanitation And Hygiene Systems And Empowerment Of Communities (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Communications, Advocacy And Public Engagement, Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Innovation, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2021, the most disadvantaged children in Mongolia benefit from increased access to and utilization of services that promote health and nutrition, including Water, Sanitation, and Hygiene (WASH) and interventions that mitigate the impact of air pollution on child survival.

description.narrative: UNICEF provided technical support to local governments on interconnecting policies and plans for climate-resilient WASH, DRR, and Winter preparedness in Mongolia.;As a result, WASH policies and capacity of local authorities were strengthened through approval and update of water safety plans (WSP) in 95.2% (59/62) of the target communities in three provinces in 2021.;To implement the WSPs, UNICEF provided technical support for designing and demonstrating climate-resilient;WASH facilities in the target areas, which was extremely important, especially in the context of the COVID–19 pandemic, helping reliable access to water and sanitation facilities to prevent and reduce community transmission.; | Status:Met | As-of Date:16/12/2021
